aorta?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["T10","T11","T12","L1","L2"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAt the \u003Cstrong\u003ET12\u003C/strong\u003E level of the vertebra, the transition from the thoracic aorta to the abdominal aorta takes place. This anatomical landmark occurs where the aorta passes through the aortic hiatus of the diaphragm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe aortic hiatus is an opening in the diaphragm that allows the aorta to pass from the thoracic cavity into the abdominal cavity. This transition is important for understanding the blood supply to the abdominal organs and is a key consideration in surgical procedures and radiological assessments.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EKnowing the exact location of this transition is crucial for clinicians to accurately interpret imaging studies and plan surgical interventions, as it helps in identifying the source of potential vascular issues and in avoiding complications during procedures involving the aorta.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The thoracic aorta transitions to the abdominal aorta at the level of the T12 vertebra.","The aortic hiatus is an opening in the diaphragm through which the aorta passes."],"references":["Netter, F. H. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: Classic Regional Approach-Ebook. 2022. Elsevier Health Sciences","Shahoud JS, Miao JH, Bolla SR. Anatomy, Thorax, Heart Aorta. [Updated 2023 Jul 24]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK538140/","Jacob, S. (2007). Human anatomy: a clinically-orientated approach. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42093"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14519"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42093","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/